  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- International Money Laundering Abatement and Anti-Terrorism Financing Act\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Laundering of monetary instruments)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from specified unlawful activity)\n\n3. State Laws:\nMany states also have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws.\n\n4. Regulatory Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC)\n- Internal Revenue Service (IRS)\n\nThese statutes generally:\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Criminalize intentional financial transactions designed to conceal the source of illegal funds\n- Impose significant penalties including fines and imprisonment\n- Establish reporting requirements for large cash transactions\n\nThe laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained money as legitimate income.",
